for selection of the discount rate for
u.s. plans, several sources of information are considered, including interest
rate market indicators and the discount rate determined by use of a yield curve
based on high-quality, noncallable bonds with cash flows that match estimated
outflows for benefit payments. for major non-u.s. plans, the discount rate is
determined by using bond portfolios with an average maturity approximating that
of the liabilities or spot yield curves, both of which areconstructed
using high-quality, local-currency-denominated bonds.
the measurement of the accumulated
postretirement benefit obligation assumes a health care cost trend rate of 4.5
percent in 2018 and subsequent years. a one-percentage-point increase in the health
care cost trend rate would increase service and interest cost by $76 million
and the postretirement benefit obligation by $862 million. a
one-percentage-point decrease in the health care cost trend rate would decrease
service and interest cost by $58 million and the postretirement benefit
obligation by $687 million.
